{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512212"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:52:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:52:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11863"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11863"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.3,0.52,0.04,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4463"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45838"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4463"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11863"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30772"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1681"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6516"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6549"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43991"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45838"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of right eye pain and blurred vision after being hit in the eye with a squash ball. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 72/min, blood pressure 128/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Ophthalmological assessment reveals a traumatic hyphema in the right eye. Intraocular pressure is normal. No other abnormalities are noted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical chloramphenicol eye drops","Eye patching for two weeks","Bed rest with semi-sitting position and topical prednisolone acetate 1% eye drops four times daily","Oral aspirin for analgesia and to prevent rebleeding ","Timolol 0.5% eye drops twice daily"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA hyphema is the accumulation of blood in the anterior chamber of the eye, usually as a result of blunt trauma. The most appropriate management for this patient with an uncomplicated traumatic \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyphema\u003C/strong\u003E is \u003Cstrong\u003Ebed rest with semi-sitting position and topical prednisolone acetate 1% eye drops four times daily\u003C/strong\u003E. Bed rest and elevation of the head aim to facilitate settling of the blood in the anterior chamber. Topical corticosteroids are used to reduce inflammation and treat any associated traumatic uveitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no clinical evidence of infection, so \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical chloramphenicol eye drops\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated. Topical antibiotics would only be appropriate if there was an associated corneal abrasion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEye patching for two weeks\u003C/strong\u003E has no role in the management of uncomplicated traumatic hyphema. Occasionally patching of both eyes may be used in patients who are not compliant with bed rest and are at high risk of rebleeding, but this is not the case for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral aspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in the management of hyphema as it may prolong the recovery time and increase the risk of rebleeding by inhibiting platelet aggregation. Oral paracetamol can be used for analgesia if required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the absence of raised intraocular pressure, \u003Cstrong\u003Etimolol 0.5% eye drops\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated. Topical beta-blockers or alpha-2 agonists would only be used if the patient developed secondary glaucoma from blockage of the trabecular meshwork by red blood cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Treatment of traumatic hyphema is aimed at treating inflammation with steroid drops, pain management, bed rest with semi-sitting position, and monitoring for and treating any associated complications."],"references":["Akriti G. Ocular trauma: Acute evaluation, cataract, glaucoma. In: EyeWiki [online]. 2021; cited 2022 Jul 15. Available at: https://eyewiki.aao.org/Ocular_Trauma:_Acute_Evaluation,_Cataract,_Glaucoma"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30772"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11863"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30772"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-22T13:55:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-22T13:55:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4463"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45838"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Dia